    <h1>RC Low-Pass Filter - SPICE AC Analysis</h1>

    <div class="ch-card">
        <h2>Circuit Components</h2>
        <ul>
            <li><strong>Resistor (R1):</strong> 1 kΩ</li>
            <li><strong>Capacitor (C1):</strong> 1 µF</li>
            <li><strong>Input (V1):</strong> AC Voltage Source (1V amplitude)</li>
        </ul>
    </div>

    <h2>Cutoff Frequency</h2>
    <div class="ch-formula">
        fc = 1 / (2πRC) = 1 / (2π × 1000 × 1×10−6) ≈ <strong>159 Hz</strong>
    </div>

    <h2>Simulation Results</h2>
    <div class="ch-grid">

        <div class="ch-col blue">
            <h3>Magnitude Response (Black Line)</h3>
            <ul>
                <li><strong>Pass Band:</strong> 0 dB gain for f &lt; 159 Hz</li>
                <li><strong>Cutoff Point:</strong> -3 dB drop at 159 Hz</li>
                <li><strong>Stop Band:</strong> -20 dB/decade roll-off</li>
                <li>At 10 kHz, attenuation is approx -35 dB</li>
            </ul>
        </div>

        <div class="ch-col red">
            <h3>Phase Response (Red Line)</h3>
            <ul>
                <li><strong>Low Freq:</strong> 0° phase shift</li>
                <li><strong>At Cutoff (fc):</strong> -45° (-0.785 rad)</li>
                <li><strong>High Freq:</strong> Approaches -90° (-π/2 rad)</li>
                <li>Capacitor introduces a lagging phase shift</li>
            </ul>
        </div>

    </div>

    <div class="ch-card green-border">
        <h2>Conclusion</h2>
        <p style="line-height: 1.6; margin: 0;">The circuit functions perfectly as a <strong>low-pass filter</strong>. It allows low-frequency signals (below 159 Hz) to pass with minimal loss while heavily attenuating high-frequency signals. The simulation results align exactly with theoretical calculations.</p>
    </div>

